{{Infobox artist | honorific_prefix = | name = <!-- include middle initial, if not specified in birth_name --> | honorific_suffix = | image = <!-- use the image's pagename; do not include the "File:" or "Image:" prefix, and do not use brackets--> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name --> | birth_date = 1913 <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living artists, {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} for dead. For living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already WIDELY published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. Treat such cases as if only the year is known, so use {{birth year and age|YYYY}} or a similar option. --> | birth_place = Paris, France | death_date = May 1983 <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | death_place = [[St. George, Staten Island]] | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} --> | nationality = | residence = St. George, Staten, Island | education = [[Université Grenoble Alpes|University of Grenoble]], [[National Academy Museum and School|National Academy of Design]] | alma_mater = | known_for = [[Marine art]] | notable_works = | style = | movement = | spouse = Susan Ames | partner = | awards = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) --> | elected = | patrons = | memorials = | website = {{URL|www.noblemaritime.org/}} | module = }}
'''John Alexander Noble''' (1913–1983) was an artist known for creating drawings, paintings, and lithographs of ships and harbors around New York City.
==Early life== Noble was born in Paris, France, in 1913. The son of painter [[John Noble (painter)|John Noble]], he moved to the United States with his family in 1919. About 1929, he started drawing and painting. While in school he was a "permanent fixture" on the McCarren line tugs, which towed schooners in New York Harbor. In the summer, he would go to sea. In 1931, he graduated from [[Friends Seminary]] and returned to France, where he studied for a year at the [[Université Grenoble Alpes|University of Grenoble]] and met his wife, Susan Ames. When he returned to New York, he studied for a year at the [[National Academy Museum and School|National Academy of Design]].<ref name="Noble Collection Bio">{{cite web |title=John A. Noble |url=http://www.noblemaritime.org/john-a-noble/ |website=The Noble Maritime Collection |access-date=August 12, 2018}}</ref>
==Career== From 1928 to 1945, Noble worked as a seaman on schooners and in marine salvage in New York Harbor. When he saw the [[Port Johnston Coal Docks]] on the [[Kill van Kull]], which had become a "great boneyard" of wooden sailing vessels, the sight of it "affected him for life". In 1941, he began to build a floating, "houseboat" studio there, made out of salvaged ship parts. From 1946, he worked as an artist full-time, voyaging through New York Harbor in a rowboat and creating—in oil paintings, charcoal drawings, sketches and lithographs—a "unique and exacting record" of the "characters, industries, and vessels" of the harbor.<ref name="Noble Collection Bio" /><ref name="NYTimesMcgill19830606" />
==Death== Noble died in May 1983. His wife had died earlier that year. At a memorial service at the [[Sailors' Snug Harbor|Snug Harbor Cultural Center]] three weeks later, 200 people, including Staten Island borough president [[Anthony Gaeta]] and Noble's two sons, spoke in remembrance. A fire boat shot plumes of water and tugboats sounded their horns.<ref name="NYTimesMcgill19830606">{{cite news |last=McGill |first=Douglas C. |title=Artist Remembered at Harbor He Loved |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/06/06/nyregion/artist-rememered-at-harbor-he-loved.html |date=June 6, 1983 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=August 12, 2018}}</ref>
==Legacy== The Noble Maritime Collection was established in 1987 to preserve and interpret Noble's work.<ref name="Noble Collection History">{{cite web |title=Museum History |url=http://www.noblemaritime.org/museum-history/ |website=The Noble Maritime Collection |access-date=August 13, 2018}}</ref>
The [[Staten Island Ferry]] ''John A. Noble'' is named for him.<ref>{{cite web |title=Staten Island Ferry Current Ferries |url=https://www.siferry.com/currentvessels.html |website=The Staten Island Ferry |access-date=August 13, 2018}}</ref>
